We have also ordered that the holy rites of the chureh be celebrated with devout reverence, under the set forms delivered to us in writing by the holy fathers, which forms, approved by the catholic saith, let none dare to change for any novelty. Also, above all, being eareful that the wine with which it is celebrated be not corrupt or turned to vinegar, and that it be red wine rather than white. Nevertheless the sacrament is rightly administered in white wine but not in vinegar3 when into vinegar it is changing all the substantial strength of the wine is lost, and water may be added in so moderate quantity that the wine may not be absorbed by the water but [rather] the water by the wine. The host should be made of wheat, round and whole, pure and without blemish, since the Lamb was without spot and not a bone

of it was broken, whence the verse,—
